// ch02 boundary table: "Calling an extern "C" function | Must be wrapped
// in unsafe { } ... No scpp compiler ever sees the C implementation to
// check it" -- this applies uniformly, even when the function has a body
// right here: extern "C" linkage itself is what marks the FFI boundary,
// regardless of whether the implementation happens to be visible in this
// translation unit. The body itself is still checked like any other
// function when it's *defined* (ch02 §2.1) -- it's *calling* it that
// needs unsafe { }.
extern "C" int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    unsafe {
        return add(3, 4);
    }
}
